# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: orbital-mechanics-applied
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] A simple example might be the case of a conventional rocket-propelled spacecraft, which achieves thrust by burning fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Such a spacecraft's delta-*v*, then, would be the change in velocity that spacecraft can achieve by burning its entire fuel load.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Delta-*v* is produced by reaction engines, such as rocket engines, and is proportional to the thrust per unit mass and the burn time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] It is used to determine the mass of propellant required for the given maneuver through the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For multiple maneuvers, delta-*v* sums linearly.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For interplanetary missions, delta-*v* is often plotted on a porkchop plot, which displays the required mission delta-*v* as a function of launch date.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] In the absence of external forces: $\Delta {v}=\int _{t_{0}}^{t_{1}}\left|{\dot {v}}\right|\,dt$ where ${\dot {v}}$ is the coordinate acceleration.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] When thrust is applied in a constant direction (⁠*v*/|*v*|⁠ is constant) this simplifies to: $\Delta {v}=|v_{1}-v_{0}|$ which is simply the magnitude of the change in velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] However, this relation does not hold in the general case: if, for instance, a constant, unidirectional acceleration is reversed after (*t*1 − *t*0)/2 then the velocity difference is 0, but delta-*v* is the same as for the non-reversed thrust.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For rockets, "absence of external forces" is taken to mean the absence of gravity drag and atmospheric drag, as well as the absence of aerostatic back pressure on the nozzle, and hence the vacuum Isp is used for calculating the vehicle's delta-*v* capacity via the rocket equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] In addition, the costs for atmospheric losses and gravity drag are added into the delta-*v* budget when dealing with launches from a planetary surface.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Orbit maneuvers are made by firing a thruster to produce a reaction force acting on the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] which is the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] If $v_{\text{exh}}$ is a non-constant function of the amount of fuel left $v_{\text{exh}}=v_{\text{exh}}(m)$ the capacity of the reaction control system is computed by the integral (**5**).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The acceleration (**2**) caused by the thruster force is just an additional acceleration to be added to the other accelerations (force per unit mass) affecting the spacecraft and the orbit can easily be propagated with a numerical algorithm including also this thruster force.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] But for many purposes, typically for studies or for maneuver optimization, they are approximated by impulsive maneuvers as illustrated in figure 1 with a $\Delta {v}$ as given by (**4**).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Like this one can for example use a "patched conics" approach modeling the maneuver as a shift from one Kepler orbit to another by an instantaneous change of the velocity vector.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] This approximation with impulsive maneuvers is in most cases very accurate, at least when chemical propulsion is used.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For low thrust systems, typically electrical propulsion systems, this approximation is less accurate.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] But even for geostationary spacecraft using electrical propulsion for out-of-plane control with thruster burn periods extending over several hours around the nodes this approximation is fair.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Delta-*v* is typically provided by the thrust of a rocket engine, but can be created by other engines.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The time-rate of change of delta-*v* is the magnitude of the acceleration *caused by the engines*, i.e., the thrust per total vehicle mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The actual acceleration vector would be found by adding thrust per mass on to the gravity vector and the vectors representing any other forces acting on the object.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The total delta-*v* needed is a good starting point for early design decisions since consideration of the added complexities are deferred to later times in the design process.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The rocket equation shows that the required amount of propellant increases exponentially with increasing delta-*v*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Therefore, in modern spacecraft propulsion systems considerable study is put into reducing the total delta-*v* needed for a given spaceflight, as well as designing spacecraft that are capable of producing larger delta-*v*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Because the mass ratios apply to any given burn, when multiple maneuvers are performed in sequence, the mass ratios multiply.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] This is just the rocket equation applied to the sum of the two maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] This is convenient since it means that delta-*v* can be calculated and simply added and the mass ratio calculated only for the overall vehicle for the entire mission.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Thus delta-*v* is commonly quoted rather than mass ratios which would require multiplication.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] When designing a trajectory, delta-*v* budget is used as a good indicator of how much propellant will be required.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Propellant usage is an exponential function of delta-*v* in accordance with the rocket equation, it will also depend on the exhaust velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] It is not possible to determine delta-*v* requirements from conservation of energy by considering only the total energy of the vehicle in the initial and final orbits since energy is carried away in the exhaust (see also below).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For example, most spacecraft are launched in an orbit with inclination fairly near to the latitude at the launch site, to take advantage of the Earth's rotational surface speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] If it is necessary, for mission-based reasons, to put the spacecraft in an orbit of different inclination, a substantial delta-*v* is required, though the specific kinetic and potential energies in the final orbit and the initial orbit are equal.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] When rocket thrust is applied in short bursts the other sources of acceleration may be negligible, and the magnitude of the velocity change of one burst may be simply approximated by the delta-*v*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] The total delta-*v* to be applied can then simply be found by addition of each of the delta-*v'*s needed at the discrete burns, even though between bursts the magnitude and direction of the velocity changes due to gravity, e.g. in an elliptic orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For examples of calculating delta-*v*, see Hohmann transfer orbit, gravitational slingshot, and Interplanetary Transport Network.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] It is also notable that large thrust can reduce gravity drag.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Delta-*v* is also required to keep satellites in orbit and is expended in propulsive orbital stationkeeping maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Since the propellant load on most satellites cannot be replenished, the amount of propellant initially loaded on a satellite may well determine its useful lifetime.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] From power considerations, it turns out that when applying delta-*v* in the direction of the velocity the specific orbital energy gained per unit delta-*v* is equal to the instantaneous speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For example, a satellite in an elliptical orbit is boosted more efficiently at high speed (that is, small altitude) than at low speed (that is, high altitude).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Another example is that when a vehicle is making a pass of a planet, burning the propellant at closest approach rather than further out gives significantly higher final speed, and this is even more so when the planet is a large one with a deep gravity field, such as Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Due to the relative positions of planets changing over time, different delta-vs are required at different launch dates.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] A diagram that shows the required delta-*v* plotted against time is sometimes called a *porkchop plot*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Such a diagram is useful since it enables calculation of a launch window, since launch should only occur when the mission is within the capabilities of the vehicle to be employed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Delta-*v* needed for various orbital manoeuvers using conventional rockets; red arrows show where optional aerobraking can be performed in that particular direction, black numbers give delta-*v* in km/s that apply in either direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Lower-delta-*v* transfers than shown can often be achieved, but involve rare transfer windows or take significantly longer, see: Orbital mechanics § Interplanetary Transport Network and fuzzy orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] For example, the Soyuz spacecraft makes a de-orbit from the ISS in two steps.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] First, it needs a delta-*v* of 2.18 m/s for a safe separation from the space station.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/delta-v] Then it needs another 128 m/s for reentry.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Although the term *escape velocity* is common, it is more accurately described as a speed than as a velocity because it is independent of direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Because gravitational force between two objects depends on their combined mass, the escape speed also depends on mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For artificial satellites and small natural objects, the mass of the object makes a negligible contribution to the combined mass, and so is often ignored.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Escape speed varies with distance from the center of the primary body, as does the velocity of an object traveling under the gravitational influence of the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] If an object is in a circular or elliptical orbit, its speed is always less than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] In contrast if it is on a hyperbolic trajectory its speed will always be higher than the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] (It will slow down as it gets to greater distance, but does so asymptotically approaching a positive speed.) An object on a parabolic trajectory will always be traveling exactly the escape speed at its current distance.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] It has precisely balanced positive kinetic energy and negative gravitational potential energy; it will always be slowing down, asymptotically approaching zero speed, but never quite stop.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Escape velocity calculations are typically used to determine whether an object will remain in the gravitational sphere of influence of a given body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For example, in solar system exploration it is useful to know whether a probe will continue to orbit the Earth or escape to a heliocentric orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] It is also useful to know how much a probe will need to slow down in order to be gravitationally captured by its destination body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Rockets do not have to reach escape velocity in a single maneuver, and objects can also use a gravity assist to siphon kinetic energy away from large bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Precise trajectory calculations require taking into account small forces like atmospheric drag, radiation pressure, and solar wind.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] A rocket under continuous or intermittent thrust (or an object climbing a space elevator) can attain escape at any non-zero speed, but the minimum amount of energy required to do so is always the same.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The value *GM* is called the standard gravitational parameter, or *μ*, and is often known more accurately than either *G* or *M* separately.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] A related quantity is the specific orbital energy which is essentially the sum of the kinetic and potential energy divided by the mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] An object has reached escape velocity when the specific orbital energy is greater than or equal to zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The existence of escape velocity can be thought of as a consequence of conservation of energy and an energy field of finite depth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Adding speed (kinetic energy) to an object expands the region of locations it can reach, until, with enough energy, everywhere to infinity becomes accessible.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The formula for escape velocity can be derived from the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For the sake of simplicity, unless stated otherwise, we assume that an object will escape the gravitational field of a uniform spherical planet by moving away from it and that the only significant force acting on the moving object is the planet's gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Imagine that a spaceship of mass *m* is initially at a distance *r* from the center of mass of the planet, whose mass is *M*, and its initial speed is equal to its escape velocity, *v*e.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] At its final state, it will be an infinite distance away from the planet, and its speed will be negligibly small.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The same result is obtained by a relativistic calculation, in which case the variable *r* represents the *radial coordinate* or *reduced circumference* of the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] where *r* is the distance between the center of the body and the point at which escape velocity is being calculated and *g* is the gravitational acceleration at that distance (i.e., the surface gravity).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For a body with a spherically symmetric distribution of mass, the escape velocity *v*e from the surface is proportional to the radius assuming constant density, and proportional to the square root of the average density *ρ*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] This escape velocity is relative to a non-rotating frame of reference, not relative to the moving surface of the planet or moon, as explained below.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The escape velocity *relative to the surface* of a rotating body depends on direction in which the escaping body travels.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The surface velocity decreases with the cosine of the geographic latitude, so space launch facilities are often located as close to the equator as feasible, e.g. the American Cape Canaveral (latitude 28°28′ N) and the French Guiana Space Centre (latitude 5°14′ N).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For an actual escape orbit, a spacecraft will accelerate steadily out of the atmosphere until it reaches the escape velocity appropriate for its altitude (which will be less than on the surface).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] In many cases, the spacecraft may be first placed in a parking orbit (e.g. a low Earth orbit at 160–2,000 km) and then accelerated to the escape velocity at that altitude, which will be slightly lower (about 11.0 km/s at a low Earth orbit of 200 km).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The required additional change in speed, however, is far less because the spacecraft already has a significant orbital speed (in low Earth orbit speed is approximately 7.8 km/s, or 28,080 km/h).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The escape velocity at a given height is ${\sqrt {2}}$ times the speed in a circular orbit at the same height, (compare this with the velocity equation in circular orbit).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] This corresponds to the fact that the potential energy with respect to infinity of an object in such an orbit is minus two times its kinetic energy, while to escape the sum of potential and kinetic energy needs to be at least zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The velocity corresponding to the circular orbit is sometimes called the **first cosmic velocity**, whereas in this context the escape velocity is referred to as the **second cosmic velocity**.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For a body in an elliptical orbit wishing to accelerate to an escape orbit the required speed will vary, and will be greatest at periapsis when the body is closest to the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] However, the orbital speed of the body will also be at its highest at this point, and the change in velocity required will be at its lowest, as explained by the Oberth effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Escape velocity can either be measured as relative to the other, central body or relative to center of mass or barycenter of the system of bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Thus for systems of two bodies, the term *escape velocity* can be ambiguous, but it is usually intended to mean the barycentric escape velocity of the less massive body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Escape velocity usually refers to the escape velocity of zero mass test particles.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] For zero mass test particles we have that the 'relative to the other' and the 'barycentric' escape velocities are the same, namely $v_{\text{e}}={\sqrt {\frac {2GM}{d}}}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] But when we can't neglect the smaller mass (say *m*) we arrive at slightly different formulas.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Because the system has to obey the law of conservation of momentum we see that both the larger and the smaller mass must be accelerated in the gravitational field.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Relative to the center of mass the velocity of the larger mass (*v*p, for planet) can be expressed in terms of the velocity of the smaller mass (*v*r, for rocket).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] where *x* = *v*/*v*e is the ratio of the original speed *v* to the escape velocity *v*e.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Unlike escape velocity, the direction (vertically up) is important to achieve maximum height.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] If an object attains exactly escape velocity, but is not directed straight away from the planet, then it will follow a curved path or trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Although this trajectory does not form a closed shape, it can be referred to as an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The shape of the trajectory will be a parabola whose focus is located at the center of mass of the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] An actual escape requires a course with a trajectory that does not intersect with the planet, or its atmosphere, since this would cause the object to crash.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] When moving away from the source, this path is called an escape orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Escape orbits are known as *C*3 = 0 orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] *C*3 is the characteristic energy, −*GM*/2*a*, where *a* is the semi-major axis length, which is infinite for parabolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] If the body has a velocity greater than escape velocity then its path will form a hyperbolic trajectory and it will have an excess hyperbolic velocity, equivalent to the extra energy the body has.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] A relatively small extra delta-*v* above that needed to accelerate to the escape speed can result in a relatively large speed at infinity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Some orbital manoeuvres make use of this fact.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] If a body in circular orbit (or at the periapsis of an elliptical orbit) accelerates along its direction of travel to escape velocity, the point of acceleration will form the periapsis of the escape trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The eventual direction of travel will be at 90 degrees to the direction at the point of acceleration.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] If the body accelerates to beyond escape velocity the eventual direction of travel will be at a smaller angle, and indicated by one of the asymptotes of the hyperbolic trajectory it is now taking.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] This means the timing of the acceleration is critical if the intention is to escape in a particular direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] This is valid for elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] In this table, the left-hand half gives the escape velocity from the visible surface of the planet or moon (which may be gaseous, for example Jupiter) relative to its centre (that is, not relative to its moving surface).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] In the right-hand half, *V*e refers to the speed relative to the central body (for example the sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] The values in the last column are variable, depending on precisely where in a body’s orbit escape velocity is reached, as the orbits are elliptical, not circular (particularly those of Mercury and Pluto).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/escape-velocity] Let *G* be the gravitational constant and let *M* be the mass of the earth (or other gravitating body) and *m* be the mass of the escaping body or projectile.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In astronautics, the **Hohmann transfer orbit** (/ˈhoʊmən/) is an orbital maneuver used to transfer a spacecraft between two orbits of different altitudes around a central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For example, a Hohmann transfer could be used to raise a satellite's orbit from low Earth orbit to geostationary orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the idealized case, the initial and target orbits are both circular and coplanar.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver is accomplished by placing the craft into an elliptical transfer orbit that is tangential to both the initial and target orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver uses two impulsive engine burns: the first establishes the transfer orbit, and the second adjusts the orbit to match the target.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Hohmann maneuver often uses the lowest possible amount of impulse (which consumes a proportional amount of delta-v, and hence propellant) to accomplish the transfer, but requires a relatively longer travel time than higher-impulse transfers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In some cases where one orbit is much larger than the other, a bi-elliptic transfer can use even less impulse, at the cost of even greater travel time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The maneuver was named after Walter Hohmann, the German scientist who published a description of it in his 1925 book *Die Erreichbarkeit der Himmelskörper* (*The Attainability of Celestial Bodies*).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Hohmann was influenced in part by the German science fiction author Kurd Lasswitz and his 1897 book *Two Planets*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When used for traveling between celestial bodies, a Hohmann transfer orbit requires that the starting and destination points be at particular locations in their orbits relative to each other.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Space missions using a Hohmann transfer must wait for this required alignment to occur, which opens a launch window.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For a mission between Earth and Mars, for example, these launch windows occur every 26 months.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A Hohmann transfer orbit also determines a fixed time required to travel between the starting and destination points; for an Earth-Mars journey this travel time is about 9 months.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When transfer is performed between orbits close to celestial bodies with significant gravitation, much less delta-v is usually required, as the Oberth effect may be employed for the burns.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] They are also often used for these situations, but low-energy transfers which take into account the thrust limitations of real engines, and take advantage of the gravity wells of both planets can be more fuel efficient.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The diagram shows a Hohmann transfer orbit to bring a spacecraft from a lower circular orbit into a higher one.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] It is an elliptic orbit that is tangential both to the lower circular orbit the spacecraft is to leave (cyan, labeled *1* on diagram) and the higher circular orbit that it is to reach (red, labeled *3* on diagram).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The transfer orbit (yellow, labeled *2* on diagram) is initiated by firing the spacecraft's engine to add energy and raise the apoapsis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] When the spacecraft reaches the apoapsis, a second engine firing adds energy to raise the periapsis, putting the spacecraft in the larger circular orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The engine is then fired again at the lower distance to slow the spacecraft into the lower circular orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Hohmann transfer orbit is based on two instantaneous velocity changes.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Extra fuel is required to compensate for the fact that the bursts take time; this is minimized by using high-thrust engines to minimize the duration of the bursts.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For transfers in Earth orbit, the two burns are labelled the *perigee burn* and the *apogee burn* (or *apogee kick*); more generally, for bodies that are not the Earth, they are labelled *periapsis* and *apoapsis* burns.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Alternatively, the second burn to circularize the orbit may be referred to as a *circularization burn*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An ideal Hohmann transfer orbit transfers between two circular orbits in the same plane and traverses exactly 180° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the real world, the destination orbit may not be circular, and may not be coplanar with the initial orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Real world transfer orbits may traverse slightly more, or slightly less, than 180° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An orbit which traverses less than 180° around the primary is called a "Type I" Hohmann transfer, while an orbit which traverses more than 180° is called a "Type II" Hohmann transfer.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Transfer orbits can go more than 360° around the primary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] These multiple-revolution transfers are sometimes referred to as Type III and Type IV, where a Type III is a Type I plus 360°, and a Type IV is a Type II plus 360°.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A Hohmann transfer orbit can be used to transfer an object's orbit toward another object, as long as they co-orbit a more massive body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the context of Earth and the Solar System, this includes any object which orbits the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] An example of where a Hohmann transfer orbit could be used is to bring an asteroid, orbiting the Sun, into contact with the Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Typically, $\mu$ is given in units of m3/s2; as such one should be sure to use meters, not kilometers, for $r_{1}$ and $r_{2}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In application to traveling from one celestial body to another it is crucial to start maneuver at the time when the two bodies are properly aligned.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Consider a geostationary transfer orbit, beginning at *r*1 = 6,678 km (altitude 300 km) and ending in a geostationary orbit with *r*2 = 42,164 km (altitude 35,786 km).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the smaller circular orbit the speed is 7.73 km/s; in the larger one, 3.07 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In the elliptical orbit in between the speed varies from 10.15 km/s at the perigee to 1.61 km/s at the apogee.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Therefore the Δv for the first burn is 10.15 − 7.73 = 2.42 km/s, for the second burn 3.07 − 1.61 = 1.46 km/s, and for both together 3.88 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is *greater* than the Δv required for an escape orbit: 10.93 − 7.73 = 3.20 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Applying a Δv at the Low Earth orbit (LEO) of only 0.78 km/s more (3.20−2.42) would give the rocket the escape velocity, which is less than the Δv of 1.46 km/s required to circularize the geosynchronous orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] As the example above demonstrates, the Δ*v* required to perform a Hohmann transfer between two circular orbits is not the greatest when the destination radius is infinite.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] (Escape speed is √2 times orbital speed, so the Δv required to escape is √2 − 1 (41.4%) of the orbital speed.) The Δv required is greatest (53.0% of smaller orbital speed) when the radius of the larger orbit is 15.5817... times that of the smaller orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For higher orbit ratios the Δ*v* required for the second burn decreases faster than the first increases.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For example, consider a spacecraft travelling from Earth to Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At the beginning of its journey, the spacecraft will already have a certain velocity and kinetic energy associated with its orbit around Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] During the burn the rocket engine applies its delta-*v*, but the kinetic energy increases as a square law, until it is sufficient to escape the planet's gravitational potential, and then burns more so as to gain enough energy to get into the Hohmann transfer orbit (around the Sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Because the rocket engine is able to make use of the initial kinetic energy of the propellant, far less delta-*v* is required over and above that needed to reach escape velocity, and the optimum situation is when the transfer burn is made at minimum altitude (low periapsis) above the planet.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The delta-*v* needed is only 3.6 km/s, only about 0.4 km/s more than needed to escape Earth, even though this results in the spacecraft going 2.9 km/s faster than the Earth as it heads off for Mars (see table below).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At the other end, the spacecraft must decelerate for the gravity of Mars to capture it.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This capture burn should optimally be done at low altitude to also make best use of the Oberth effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Therefore, relatively small amounts of thrust at either end of the trip are needed to arrange the transfer compared to the free space situation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] However, with any Hohmann transfer, the alignment of the two planets in their orbits is crucial – the destination planet and the spacecraft must arrive at the same point in their respective orbits around the Sun at the same time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This requirement for alignment gives rise to the concept of launch windows.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The term lunar transfer orbit (LTO) is used for the Moon.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] It is possible to apply the formula given above to calculate the Δv in km/s needed to enter a Hohmann transfer orbit to arrive at various destinations from Earth (assuming circular orbits for the planets).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In this table, the column labeled "Δv to enter Hohmann orbit from Earth's orbit" gives the change from Earth's velocity to the velocity needed to get on a Hohmann ellipse whose other end will be at the desired distance from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The column labeled "LEO height" gives the velocity needed (in a non-rotating frame of reference centered on the earth) when 300 km above the Earth's surface.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is obtained by adding to the specific kinetic energy the square of the escape velocity (10.93 km/s) from this height.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The column "LEO" is simply the previous speed minus the LEO orbital speed of 7.73 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Note that in most cases, Δ*v* from LEO is less than the Δ*v* to enter Hohmann orbit from Earth's orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] To get to the Sun, it is actually not necessary to use a Δ*v* of 24 km/s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] One can use 8.8 km/s to go very far away from the Sun, then use a negligible Δ*v* to bring the angular momentum to zero, and then fall into the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This is also known as a bi-elliptic transfer, which is a sequence of two Hohmann transfers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Also, the table does not give the values that would apply when using the Moon for a gravity assist.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] There are also possibilities of using one planet, like Venus which is the easiest to get to, to assist getting to other planets or the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The bi-elliptic transfer consists of two half-elliptic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] From the initial orbit, a first burn expends delta-v to boost the spacecraft into the first transfer orbit with an apoapsis at some point $r_{b}$ away from the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] At this point a second burn sends the spacecraft into the second elliptical orbit with periapsis at the radius of the final desired orbit, where a third burn is performed, injecting the spacecraft into the desired orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The idea of the bi-elliptical transfer trajectory was first published by Ary Sternfeld in 1934.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Low-thrust engines can perform an approximation of a Hohmann transfer orbit, by creating a gradual enlargement of the initial circular orbit through carefully timed engine firings.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This requires a change in velocity (delta-*v*) that is greater than the two-impulse transfer orbit and takes longer to complete.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Engines such as ion thrusters are more difficult to analyze with the delta-*v* model.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] These engines offer a very low thrust and at the same time, much higher delta-*v* budget, much higher specific impulse, lower mass of fuel and engine.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] A 2-burn Hohmann transfer maneuver would be impractical with such a low thrust; the maneuver mainly optimizes the use of fuel, but in this situation there is relatively plenty of it.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] If only low-thrust maneuvers are planned on a mission, then continuously firing a low-thrust, but very high-efficiency engine might generate a higher delta-*v* and at the same time use less propellant than a conventional chemical rocket engine.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Going from one circular orbit to another by gradually changing the radius simply requires the same delta-*v* as the difference between the two speeds.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Such maneuver requires more delta-*v* than a 2-burn Hohmann transfer maneuver, but does so with continuous low thrust rather than the short applications of high thrust.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The amount of propellant mass used measures the efficiency of the maneuver plus the hardware employed for it.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The total delta-*v* used measures the efficiency of the maneuver only.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For electric propulsion systems, which tend to be low-thrust, the high efficiency of the propulsive system usually compensates for the higher delta-V compared to the more efficient Hohmann maneuver.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] Transfer orbits using electrical propulsion or low-thrust engines optimize the transfer time to reach the final orbit and not the delta-v as in the Hohmann transfer orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] For geostationary orbit, the initial orbit is set to be supersynchronous and by thrusting continuously in the direction of the velocity at apogee, the transfer orbit transforms to a circular geosynchronous one.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] This method however takes much longer to achieve due to the low thrust injected into the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] In 1997, a set of orbits known as the Interplanetary Transport Network (ITN) was published, providing even lower propulsive delta-*v* (though much slower and longer) paths between different orbits than Hohmann transfer orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Interplanetary Transport Network is different in nature than Hohmann transfers because Hohmann transfers assume only one large body whereas the Interplanetary Transport Network does not.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/hohmann-transfer-orbit] The Interplanetary Transport Network is able to achieve the use of less propulsive delta-*v* by employing gravity assist from the planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In astronomy, **Kepler's laws of planetary motion** give good approximations for the orbits of planets around the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] They were published by Johannes Kepler from 1608 to 1621 in three works *Astronomia nova,* *Harmonice Mundi* and *Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The laws were based on Kepler's concept of solar fibrils adapted to the accurate astronomical data of Tycho Brahe.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] These laws replaced the circular orbits and epicycles of Copernicus's heliostatic model of the planets with a heliocentric model that described elliptical orbits with planetary velocities that vary accordingly.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] A line segment joining a planet and the Sun sweeps out equal areas during equal intervals of time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The square of a planet's orbital period is proportional to the cube of the length of the semi-major axis of its orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The elliptical orbits of planets were indicated by calculations of the orbit of Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] From this, Kepler inferred that other bodies in the Solar System, including those farther away from the Sun, also have elliptical orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The second law establishes that when a planet is closer to the Sun, it travels faster.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The third law expresses that the farther a planet is from the Sun, the longer its orbital period.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Johannes Kepler's laws improved the model of Copernicus.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The Sun is approximately at the center of the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The speed of the planet in the main orbit is constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Despite being correct in saying that the planets revolved around the Sun, Copernicus was incorrect in defining their orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The Sun is *not* at the center but at a *focal point* of the elliptical orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Neither the linear speed nor the angular speed of the planet in the orbit is constant, but the *area speed* (closely linked historically with the concept of angular momentum) is constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The eccentricity of the orbit of the Earth makes the time from the March equinox to the September equinox, around 186 days, unequal to the time from the September equinox to the March equinox, around 179 days.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] A diameter would cut the orbit into equal parts, but the plane through the Sun parallel to the equator of the Earth cuts the orbit into two parts with areas in a 186 to 179 ratio.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The areas swept out in an ellipse will differ by twice the area of a triangle with the focus and the two minor axis points as vertices.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This triangle has area $bc,$ where b is the semi-minor axis length, and c is the linear eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Thus the difference in areas is $2bc.$ Since the eccentricity is given by $e={\frac {c}{a}}$ (where a is the semi-major axis), we have $e={\frac {A_{\Delta }}{2ab}},$ where $A_{\Delta }$ is the difference in swept areas.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The accuracy of this calculation requires that the two dates chosen be along the elliptical orbit's minor axis and that the midpoints of each half be along the major axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] As the two dates chosen here are equinoxes, this will be correct when perihelion, the date the Earth is closest to the Sun, falls on a solstice.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The current perihelion, near January 4, is fairly close to the solstice of December 21 or 22, but this difference (14–15 days) is actually bigger than our difference in inter-equinox times (7 days), which explains our substantial error.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's laws were developed based on a physical theory of planetary motion in which the Sun emitted magnetic fibrils which pulled the planets into orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The fibrils were somewhat elastic allowing non-circular motion driven by the inertia of the planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In *Astronomia nova* (1609), Kepler articulated his first law, showing that Mars' orbit is elliptical, having found them by analyzing the astronomical observations of Tycho Brahe.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler had believed in the Copernican model of the Solar System, which called for circular orbits, but he could not reconcile Brahe's highly precise observations with a circular fit to Mars' orbit – Mars coincidentally having the highest eccentricity of all planets except Mercury.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In his *Astronomia nova* (1609), Kepler did not present his second law in its modern form.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] He did that only in his *Epitome Astronomiae Copernicanae* of 1621.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler had two versions of the second law, related in a qualitative sense: the first "distance law" and later the "area law".
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The distance form was only correct for orbits that were almost circular, but the area form was correct for all elliptical orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The "area law" is what became the second law in the set of three.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This law had little impact on astronomy because calculations of planetary positions using the law were approximate and time consuming.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The second law, in the "area law" form, was contested by Nicolaus Mercator in a book from 1664, but by 1670 his *Philosophical Transactions* were in its favour.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] As the century proceeded it became more widely accepted.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's third law was published in 1619 in his *Harmonice Mundi*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In 1621, Kepler noted that his third law applies to the four brightest moons of Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Godefroy Wendelin, the first well-known astronomer to adopt Kepler's laws, gave a detailed account of the third law in 1652.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's work had little initial impact.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] His work was a strong defense of Copernicanism which had fallen out of fashion in part because of opposition by Tycho Brahe.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In 1627 Kepler published the Rudolphine Tables containing many accurate astronomical observations accumulated by Brahe.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The breadth and accuracy of the tables allowed astronomers to compare Kepler's formula to good quality data.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] At first these difficult calculations were off putting, but once undertaken more astronomers became convinced of Kepler's approach.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The reception in Germany changed noticeably between 1688, the year in which Newton's *Principia* was published and was taken to be basically Copernican, and 1690, by which time work of Gottfried Leibniz on Kepler had been published.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Newton understood that the second law is not special to the inverse-square law of gravitation, being a consequence just of the radial nature of that law, whereas the other laws do depend on the inverse-square form of the attraction.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] It took nearly two centuries for the current formulation of Kepler's work to take on its settled form.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Voltaire's *Eléments de la philosophie de Newton* (*Elements of Newton's Philosophy*) of 1738 was the first publication to use the terminology of "laws".
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The *Biographical Encyclopedia of Astronomers* in its article on Kepler (p.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] 620) states that the terminology of scientific laws for these discoveries was current at least from the time of Joseph de Lalande.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] It was the exposition of Robert Small, in *An account of the astronomical discoveries of Kepler* (1814) that made up the set of three laws, by adding in the third.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Small also claimed, against the history, that these were empirical laws, based on inductive reasoning.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The mathematical model of the kinematics of a planet subject to the laws allows a large range of further calculations.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] For an ellipse, 0 < *ε* < 1; in the limiting case *ε* = 0, the orbit is a circle with the Sun at the centre (i.e. where there is zero eccentricity).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] At *θ* = 90° and at *θ* = 270°, the distance is equal to p .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The special case of a circle is *ε* = 0, resulting in *r* = *p* = *r*min = *r*max = *a* = *b* and *A* = *πr*2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The orbital radius and angular velocity of the planet in the elliptical orbit will vary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This is shown in the animation: the planet travels faster when closer to the Sun, then slower when farther from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's second law states that the blue sector has constant area.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The propelling force from the Sun is inversely proportional to the distance from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler reasoned this, believing that gravity spreading in three dimensions would be a waste, since the planets inhabited a plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Thus, an inverse instead of the [correct] inverse square law.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Because Kepler believed that force would be proportional to velocity, it followed from statements #1 and #2 that velocity would be inverse to the distance from the sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] That force is proportional to velocity is an incorrect tenet of Aristotelian physics, but the errors of assumption in statements #2 and #3 essentially cancel, so that it is approximately true that velocity is inverse to the distance from the sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Since velocity is inverse to time, the distance from the sun would be proportional to the time to cover a small piece of the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This is approximately true for elliptical orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The area swept out is proportional to the overall time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The orbits of a planet are circular (Kepler discovered his second law before his first law, which contradicts this).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Nevertheless, the result of the second law is exactly true, as it is logically equivalent to the conservation of angular momentum, which is true for any body experiencing a radially symmetric force.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] A correct proof can be shown through this.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Since any radial force will produce no torque on the planet's motion, angular momentum will be conserved.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The area enclosed by the elliptical orbit is $\pi ab$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In the following example animations, the red ray rotates at a constant angular velocity and with the same orbital time period as the planet, $T=1$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] *S*: Sun at the primary focus, *C*: Centre of ellipse, *S*′: The secondary focus.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] In each case, the area of all sectors depicted is identical.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This captures the relationship between the distance of planets from the Sun, and their orbital periods.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler enunciated in 1619 this third law in a laborious attempt to determine what he viewed as the "music of the spheres" according to precise laws, and express it in terms of musical notation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] It was therefore known as the *harmonic law*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The original form of this law (referring to not the semi-major axis, but rather a "mean distance") holds true only for planets with small eccentricities near zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] A more detailed derivation can be done with general elliptical orbits, instead of circles, as well as orbiting the center of mass, instead of just the large mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This results in replacing a circular radius r with the semi-major axis a of the elliptical relative motion of one mass relative to the other, as well as replacing the large mass M with $M+m$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] However, with planet masses being so much smaller than the Sun, this correction is often ignored.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler became aware of John Napier's recent invention of logarithms and log–log graphs before he discovered the pattern.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Isaac Newton computed in his *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* the acceleration of a planet moving according to Kepler's first and second laws.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The *magnitude* of the acceleration is inversely proportional to the square of the planet's distance from the Sun (the *inverse square law*).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] This implies that the Sun may be the physical cause of the acceleration of planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] However, Newton states in his *Principia* that he considers forces from a mathematical point of view, not a physical, thereby taking an instrumentalist view.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Moreover, he does not assign a cause to gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Newton defined the force acting on a planet to be the product of its mass and the acceleration (see Newton's laws of motion).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The force acting on a planet is directly proportional to the mass of the planet and is inversely proportional to the square of its distance from the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The Sun plays an unsymmetrical part, which is unjustified.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The force between two bodies is in direct proportion to the product of their masses and in inverse proportion to the square of the distance between them.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] As the planets have small masses compared to that of the Sun, the orbits conform approximately to Kepler's laws.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Newton's model improves upon Kepler's model, and fits actual observations more accurately.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Below comes the detailed calculation of the acceleration of a planet moving according to Kepler's first and second laws.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's second law says that $r^{2}{\dot {\theta }}=nab$ is constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The transversal acceleration $a_{\theta }$ is zero: ${\frac {d\left(r^{2}{\dot {\theta }}\right)}{dt}}=r\left(2{\dot {r}}{\dot {\theta }}+r{\ddot {\theta }}\right)=ra_{\theta }=0.$ So the acceleration of a planet obeying Kepler's second law is directed towards the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Since mean motion $n=2\pi /T$ , where T is the period, according to Kepler's third law, $\alpha$ has the same value for all the planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] So the inverse square law for planetary accelerations applies throughout the entire Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The inverse-square law is a differential equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The solutions to this differential equation include the Keplerian motions, as shown, but they also include motions where the orbit is a hyperbola or parabola or a straight line (see Kepler orbit).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] According to Newton's third law, the Sun is attracted to the planet by a force of the same magnitude.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Since the force is proportional to the mass of the planet, under the symmetric consideration, it should also be proportional to the mass of the Sun, $m_{\text{Sun}}$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] So $\alpha =Gm_{\text{Sun}},$ where G is the gravitational constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] So this Earth moves around the Sun according to Kepler's laws.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] But Keplerian approximation is the basis for perturbation calculations (see Lunar theory).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler used his two first laws to compute the position of a planet as a function of time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] His method involves the solution of a transcendental equation called Kepler's equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Compute the mean anomaly *M* = *nt*, where *t* is the time since perihelion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Compute the eccentric anomaly *E* by solving Kepler's equation: $M=E-\varepsilon \sin E,$ where $\varepsilon$ is the eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Compute the heliocentric distance $r=a(1-\varepsilon \cos E),$ where a is the semi-major axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The important special case of circular orbit, *ε* = 0, gives *θ* = *E* = *M*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Because the uniform circular motion was considered to be *normal*, a deviation from this motion was considered an anomaly.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The proof of this procedure is shown below.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The problem is to compute the polar coordinates (*r*, *θ*) of the planet from the time since perihelion, *t*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The area swept since perihelion, $|zsp|={\frac {b}{a}}\cdot |zsx|={\frac {b}{a}}\cdot |zcy|={\frac {b}{a}}\cdot {\frac {a^{2}M}{2}}={\frac {abM}{2}},$ is by Kepler's second law proportional to time since perihelion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] So the mean anomaly *M* is proportional to time *t* since perihelion: $M=nt,$ where *n* is the mean motion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] When the mean anomaly *M* is computed, the goal is to compute the true anomaly *θ*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] The function *θ* = *f*(*M*) is, however, not elementary.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Kepler's solution is to use $E=\angle zcx,$ with *x* as seen from the centre, the eccentric anomaly as an intermediate variable, and first compute *E* as a function of *M* by solving Kepler's equation below, and then compute the true anomaly *θ* from the eccentric anomaly *E*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Division by *a*2/2 gives Kepler's equation $M=E-\varepsilon \sin E.$ This equation gives *M* as a function of *E*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Determining *E* for a given *M* is the inverse problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Iterative numerical algorithms are commonly used.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Having computed the eccentric anomaly *E*, the next step is to calculate the true anomaly *θ*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Note that Cartesian position coordinates with reference to the center of ellipse are (*a* cos *E*, *b* sin *E*).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] True anomaly would be arctan(*r**y*/*r**x*), magnitude of *r* would be √*r* · *r*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/kepler-s-laws-of-planetary-motion] Multiplying by 1 + *ε* gives the result $(1-\varepsilon )\tan ^{2}{\frac {\theta }{2}}=(1+\varepsilon )\tan ^{2}{\frac {E}{2}}.$ This is the third step in the connection between time and position in the orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] In celestial mechanics, the **Lagrange points** (/ləˈɡrɑːndʒ/), also called the **Lagrangian points** or **libration points**, are points of equilibrium for small-mass objects under the gravitational influence of two massive orbiting bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Mathematically, this involves the solution of the restricted three-body problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Normally, the two massive bodies exert an unbalanced gravitational force at a point, altering the orbit of any other celestial body at that point.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] At the Lagrange points, the gravitational forces of the two large bodies and the centrifugal pseudo-force balance each other.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This can make Lagrange points an excellent location for satellites, as orbit corrections, and hence fuel requirements, needed to maintain the desired orbit are kept at a minimum.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] For any combination of two orbital bodies, there are five Lagrange points, L1 to L5, all in the orbital plane of the two large bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] There are five Lagrange points for the Sun–Earth system, and five *different* Lagrange points for the Earth–Moon system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] L1, L2, and L3 are on the line through the centers of the two large bodies, while L4 and L5 each act as the third vertex of an equilateral triangle formed with the centers of the two large bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] When the mass ratio of the two bodies is large enough, the L4 and L5 points are stable points, meaning that objects can orbit them and that they have a tendency to pull objects into them.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Several planets have trojan asteroids near their L4 and L5 points with respect to the Sun; Jupiter has more than one million of these trojans.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Some Lagrange points are being used for space exploration.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Two important Lagrange points in the Sun–Earth system are L1, between the Sun and Earth, and L2, on the same line at the opposite side of the Earth; both are well outside the Moon's orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Currently, an artificial satellite called the Deep Space Climate Observatory (DSCOVR) is located at L1 to study solar wind coming toward Earth from the Sun and to monitor Earth's climate, by taking images and sending them back.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The James Webb Space Telescope, a powerful infrared space observatory, is located at L2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This allows the satellite's sunshield to protect the telescope from the light and heat of the Sun, Earth and Moon simultaneously with no need to rotate the sunshield.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope is also planned for operation at L2 beginning in 2027.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L1 and L2 Lagrange points are located about 1,500,000 km (930,000 mi) from Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The European Space Agency's earlier Gaia telescope, and its newly launched Euclid, also occupy orbits around L2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Gaia keeps a tighter Lissajous orbit around L2, while Euclid follows a halo orbit similar to JWST.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The three collinear Lagrange points (L1, L2, L3) were discovered by the Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler around 1750, a decade before the Italian-born Joseph-Louis Lagrange discovered the remaining two (L4 and L5).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] In 1772, Lagrange published an "Essay on the three-body problem".
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] In the first chapter he considered the general three-body problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] From that, in the second chapter, he demonstrated two special constant-pattern solutions, the collinear and the equilateral, for any three masses, with circular orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L1 point lies on the line defined between the two large masses *M*1 and *M*2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] It is the point where the gravitational attraction of *M*2 and that of *M*1 combine to produce an equilibrium.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] An object that orbits the Sun more closely than Earth would typically have a shorter orbital period than Earth, but that ignores the effect of Earth's gravitational pull.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] If the object is directly between Earth and the Sun, then Earth's gravity counteracts some of the Sun's pull on the object, increasing the object's orbital period.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The closer to Earth the object is, the greater this effect is.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] At the L1 point, the object's orbital period becomes exactly equal to Earth's orbital period.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] L1 is about 1.5 million kilometers, or 0.01 au, from Earth in the direction of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L2 point lies on the line through the two large masses beyond the smaller of the two.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Here, the combined gravitational forces of the two large masses balance the centrifugal force on a body at L2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] On the opposite side of Earth from the Sun, the orbital period of an object would normally be greater than Earth's.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The extra pull of Earth's gravity decreases the object's orbital period, and at the L2 point, that orbital period becomes equal to Earth's.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Like L1, L2 is about 1.5 million kilometers or 0.01 au from Earth (away from the sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] An example of a spacecraft designed to operate near the Earth–Sun L2 is the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Earlier examples include the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe and its successor, *Planck*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L3 point lies on the line defined by the two large masses, beyond the larger of the two.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Within the Sun–Earth system, the L3 point exists on the opposite side of the Sun, a little outside Earth's orbit and slightly farther from the barycenter of the Earth–Sun system than Earth is.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This placement occurs because the Sun is also affected by Earth's gravity and so orbits around the two bodies' barycenter, which is well inside the body of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] An object at Earth's distance from the Sun would have an orbital period of one year if only the Sun's gravity is considered.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] But an object on the opposite side of the Sun from Earth and directly in line with both "feels" Earth's gravity adding slightly to the Sun's and therefore must orbit a little farther from the barycenter of Earth and Sun in order to have the same 1-year period.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] It is at the L3 point that the combined pull of Earth and Sun causes the object to orbit with the same period as Earth, in effect orbiting an Earth+Sun mass with the Earth-Sun barycenter at one focus of its orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] For the above argument, it is important to distinguish between the center of the Sun and the Earth-Sun barycenter.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The distance between the L3 point and the center of the Sun is actually *smaller* than the distance between the center of the Earth and the center of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L4 and L5 points lie at the third vertices of the two equilateral triangles in the plane of orbit whose common base is the line between the centers of the two masses, such that the point lies 60° ahead of (L4) or behind (L5) the smaller mass with regard to its orbit around the larger mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The triangular points (L4 and L5) are stable equilibria, provided that the ratio of ⁠*M*1/*M*2⁠ is greater than 24.96.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This is the case for the Sun–Earth system, the Sun–Jupiter system, and, by a smaller margin, the Earth–Moon system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The points L1, L2, and L3 are positions of unstable equilibrium.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Any object orbiting at L1, L2, or L3 will tend to fall out of orbit; it is therefore rare to find natural objects there, and spacecraft inhabiting these areas must employ a small but critical amount of station keeping in order to maintain their position.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Due to the natural stability of L4 and L5, it is common for natural objects to be found orbiting in those Lagrange points of planetary systems.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Objects that inhabit those points are generically referred to as 'trojans' or 'trojan asteroids'.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The name derives from the names that were given to asteroids discovered orbiting at the Sun–Jupiter L4 and L5 points, which were taken from mythological characters appearing in Homer's *Iliad*, an epic poem set during the Trojan War.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Asteroids at the L4 point, ahead of Jupiter, are named after Greek characters in the *Iliad* and referred to as the "Greek camp".
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Those at the L5 point are named after Trojan characters and referred to as the "Trojan camp".
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Both camps are considered to be types of trojan bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] As the Sun and Jupiter are the two most massive objects in the Solar System, there are more known Sun–Jupiter trojans than for any other pair of bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Objects which are on horseshoe orbits are sometimes erroneously described as trojans, but do not occupy Lagrange points.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Known objects on horseshoe orbits include 3753 Cruithne with Earth, and Saturn's moons Epimetheus and Janus.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Lagrange points are the constant-pattern solutions of the restricted three-body problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] For example, given two massive bodies in orbits around their common barycenter, there are five positions in space where a third body, of comparatively negligible mass, could be placed so as to maintain its position relative to the two massive bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This occurs because the combined gravitational forces of the two massive bodies provide the exact centripetal force required to maintain the circular motion that matches their orbital motion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The quantity in parentheses on the right is the distance of L1 from the center of mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] We may also write this as: ${\frac {M_{2}}{r^{3}}}\approx 3{\frac {M_{1}}{R^{3}}}$ Since the tidal effect of a body is proportional to its mass divided by the distance cubed, this means that the tidal effect of the smaller body at the L1 or at the L2 point is about three times of that body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The ratio of diameter to distance gives the angle subtended by the body, showing that viewed from these two Lagrange points, the apparent sizes of the two bodies will be similar, especially if the density of the smaller one is about thrice that of the larger, as in the case of the Earth and the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The same remarks about tidal influence and apparent size apply as for the L1 point.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Looking toward the Sun from L2 one sees an annular eclipse.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] It is necessary for a spacecraft, like Gaia, to follow a Lissajous orbit or a halo orbit around L2 in order for its solar panels to get full sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Thus the distance from L3 to the larger object is less than the separation of the two objects (although the distance between L3 and the barycentre is greater than the distance between the smaller object and the barycentre).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The reason these points are in balance is that at L4 and L5 the distances to the two masses are equal.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Accordingly, the gravitational forces from the two massive bodies are in the same ratio as the masses of the two bodies, and so the resultant force acts through the barycenter of the system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Additionally, the geometry of the triangle ensures that the resultant acceleration is to the distance from the barycenter in the same ratio as for the two massive bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The general triangular configuration was discovered by Lagrange working on the three-body problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The terms in this function represent respectively: force from *M*1; force from *M*2; and centripetal force.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The points L3, L1, L2 occur where the acceleration is zero — see chart at right.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Positive acceleration is acceleration towards the right of the chart and negative acceleration is towards the left; that is why acceleration has opposite signs on opposite sides of the gravity wells.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Although the L1, L2, and L3 points are nominally unstable, there are quasi-stable periodic orbits called *halo orbits* around these points in a three-body system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] A full *n*-body dynamical system such as the Solar System does not contain these periodic orbits, but does contain quasi-periodic (i.e. bounded but not precisely repeating) orbits following Lissajous-curve trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] These quasi-periodic Lissajous orbits are what most of Lagrangian-point space missions have used until now.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Although they are not perfectly stable, a modest effort of station keeping keeps a spacecraft in a desired Lissajous orbit for a long time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] For Sun–Earth-L1 missions, it is preferable for the spacecraft to be in a large-amplitude (100,000–200,000 km or 62,000–124,000 mi) Lissajous orbit around L1 than to stay at L1, because the line between Sun and Earth has increased solar interference on Earth–spacecraft communications.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Similarly, a large-amplitude Lissajous orbit around L2 keeps a probe out of Earth's shadow and therefore ensures continuous illumination of its solar panels.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L4 and L5 points are stable provided that the mass of the primary body (e.g. the Earth) is at least 25 times the mass of the secondary body (e.g. the Moon), The Earth is over 81 times the mass of the Moon (the Moon is 1.23% of the mass of the Earth).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Although the L4 and L5 points are found at the top of a "hill", as in the effective potential contour plot above, they are nonetheless stable.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The reason for the stability is a second-order effect: as a body moves away from the exact Lagrange position, Coriolis acceleration (which depends on the velocity of an orbiting object and cannot be modeled as a contour map) curves the trajectory into a path around (rather than away from) the point.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Because the source of stability is the Coriolis force, the resulting orbits can be stable, but generally are not planar, but "three-dimensional": they lie on a warped surface intersecting the ecliptic plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The kidney-shaped orbits typically shown nested around L4 and L5 are the projections of the orbits on a plane (e.g. the ecliptic) and not the full 3-D orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] This table lists sample values of L1, L2, and L3 within the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Calculations assume the two bodies orbit in a perfect circle with separation equal to the semimajor axis and no other bodies are nearby.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Distances are measured from the larger body's center of mass (but see barycenter especially in the case of Earth-Moon and Sun-Jupiter) with L3 showing a negative direction.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The percentage columns show the distance from the orbit compared to the semimajor axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Sun–Earth L1 is suited for making observations of the Sun–Earth system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Objects here are never shadowed by Earth or the Moon and, if observing Earth, always view the sunlit hemisphere.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The first mission of this type was the 1978 International Sun Earth Explorer 3 (ISEE-3) mission used as an interplanetary early warning storm monitor for solar disturbances.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Since June 2015, DSCOVR has orbited the L1 point.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Conversely, it is also useful for space-based solar telescopes, because it provides an uninterrupted view of the Sun and any space weather (including the solar wind and coronal mass ejections) reaches L1 up to an hour before Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Solar and heliospheric missions currently located around L1 include the Solar and Heliospheric Observatory, Wind, Aditya-L1 Mission and the Advanced Composition Explorer.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Planned missions include the Interstellar Mapping and Acceleration Probe(IMAP) and the NEO Surveyor.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Recently explored concepts have also included the positioning of a large occulting membrane at the L1 point, as part of a space-based solar radiation management solution to mitigate global warming.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Sun–Earth L2 is a good spot for space-based observatories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Because an object around L2 will maintain the same relative position with respect to the Sun and Earth, shielding and calibration are much simpler.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] It is, however, slightly beyond the reach of Earth's umbra, so solar radiation is not completely blocked at L2.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Spacecraft generally orbit around L2, avoiding partial eclipses of the Sun to maintain a constant temperature.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The James Webb Space Telescope was positioned in a halo orbit about L2 on 24 January 2022.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Sun–Earth L1 and L2 are saddle points and exponentially unstable with time constant of roughly 23 days.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Satellites at these points will wander off in a few months unless course corrections are made.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The Sun–Earth L3, however, is a weak saddle point and exponentially unstable with time constant of roughly 150 years.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Moreover, it could not contain a natural object, large or small, for very long because the gravitational forces of the other planets are stronger than that of Earth (for example, Venus comes within 0.3 AU of this L3 every 20 months).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] A spacecraft orbiting near Sun–Earth L3 would be able to closely monitor the evolution of active sunspot regions before they rotate into a geoeffective position, so that a seven-day early warning could be issued by the NOAA Space Weather Prediction Center.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Moreover, a satellite near Sun–Earth L3 would provide very important observations not only for Earth forecasts, but also for deep space support (Mars predictions and for crewed missions to near-Earth asteroids).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] In 2010, spacecraft transfer trajectories to Sun–Earth L3 were studied and several designs were considered.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Earth–Moon L1 allows comparatively easy access to lunar and Earth orbits with minimal change in velocity and this has as an advantage to position a habitable space station intended to help transport cargo and personnel to the Moon and back.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The SMART-1 mission passed through the L1 Lagrangian Point on 11 November 2004 and passed into the area dominated by the Moon's gravitational influence.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Earth–Moon L2 has been used for a communications satellite covering the Moon's far side, for example, Queqiao, launched in 2018, and would be "an ideal location" for a propellant depot as part of the proposed depot-based space transportation architecture.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Earth–Moon L4 and L5 are the locations for the Kordylewski dust clouds.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The L5 Society's name comes from the L4 and L5 Lagrangian points in the Earth–Moon system proposed as locations for their huge rotating space habitats.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Both positions are also proposed for communication satellites covering the Moon alike communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit cover the Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] Scientists at the B612 Foundation were planning to use Venus's L3 point to position their planned Sentinel telescope, which aimed to look back towards Earth's orbit and compile a catalog of near-Earth asteroids.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] In 2017, the idea of positioning a magnetic dipole shield at the Sun–Mars L1 point for use as an artificial magnetosphere for Mars was discussed at a NASA conference.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/lagrange-point] The idea is that this would protect the planet's atmosphere from the Sun's radiation and solar winds.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In spaceflight, an **orbital maneuver** (otherwise known as a **burn**) is the use of propulsion systems to change the orbit of a spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] For spacecraft far from Earth, an orbital maneuver is called a *deep-space maneuver (DSM)*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] When a spacecraft is not conducting a maneuver, especially in a transfer orbit, it is said to be *coasting*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The Tsiolkovsky rocket equation, or ideal rocket equation, can be useful for analysis of maneuvers by vehicles using rocket propulsion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] A rocket applies acceleration to itself (a thrust) by expelling part of its mass at high speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The rocket itself moves due to the conservation of momentum.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The applied change in velocity of each maneuver is referred to as delta-v ( $\Delta \mathbf {v} \,$ ).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The delta-v for all the expected maneuvers are estimated for a mission are summarized in a delta-v budget.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] With a good approximation of the delta-v budget designers can estimate the propellant required for planned maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] An **impulsive maneuver** is the mathematical model of a maneuver as an instantaneous change in the spacecraft's velocity (magnitude and/or direction) as illustrated in figure 1.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] It is the limit case of a burn to generate a particular amount of delta-v, as the burn time tends to zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In the physical world no truly instantaneous change in velocity is possible as this would require an "infinite force" applied during an "infinitely short time" but as a mathematical model it in most cases describes the effect of a maneuver on the orbit very well.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The off-set of the velocity vector after the end of real burn from the velocity vector at the same time resulting from the theoretical impulsive maneuver is only caused by the difference in gravitational force along the two paths (red and black in figure 1) which in general is small.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In the planning phase of space missions designers will first approximate their intended orbital changes using impulsive maneuvers that greatly reduces the complexity of finding the correct orbital transitions.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Applying a low thrust over a longer period of time is referred to as a **non-impulsive maneuver**.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] 'Non-impulsive' refers to the momentum changing slowly over a long time, as in electrically powered spacecraft propulsion, rather than by a short impulse.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Another term is *finite burn*, where the word "finite" is used to mean "non-zero", or practically, again: over a longer period.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] For a few space missions, such as those including a space rendezvous, high fidelity models of the trajectories are required to meet the mission goals.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Calculating a "finite" burn requires a detailed model of the spacecraft and its thrusters.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The most important of details include: mass, center of mass, moment of inertia, thruster positions, thrust vectors, thrust curves, specific impulse, thrust centroid offsets, and fuel consumption, although the spacecraft is often modelled as a point mass for preliminary design purposes.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] A low-thrust trajectory is typically computed using optimal control theory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In astronautics, the **Oberth effect** is where the use of a rocket engine when travelling at high speed generates much more useful energy than one at low speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Oberth effect occurs because the propellant has more usable energy (due to its kinetic energy on top of its chemical potential energy) and it turns out that the vehicle is able to employ this kinetic energy to generate more mechanical power.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] It is named after Hermann Oberth, the Austro-Hungarian-born, German physicist and a founder of modern rocketry, who apparently first described the effect.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Since the Oberth maneuver happens in a very limited time (while still at low altitude), to generate a high impulse the engine necessarily needs to achieve high thrust (impulse is by definition the time multiplied by thrust).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Thus the Oberth effect is far less useful for low-thrust engines, such as ion thrusters.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Historically, a lack of understanding of this effect led investigators to conclude that interplanetary travel would require completely impractical amounts of propellant, as without it, enormous amounts of energy are needed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In astrodynamics a gravity assist maneuver, gravitational slingshot or swing-by is the use of the relative movement and gravity of a planet or other celestial body to alter the trajectory of a spacecraft, typically in order to save propellant, time, and expense.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Gravity assistance can be used to accelerate, decelerate and/or re-direct the path of a spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The "assist" is provided by the motion (orbital angular momentum) of the gravitating body as it pulls on the spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The technique was first proposed as a mid-course maneuver in 1961, and used by interplanetary probes from *Mariner 10* onwards, including the two *Voyager* probes' notable fly-bys of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Orbit insertion maneuvers leave a spacecraft in a destination orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In contrast, orbit injection maneuvers occur when a spacecraft enters a transfer orbit, e.g. trans-lunar injection (TLI), trans-Mars injection (TMI) and trans-Earth injection (TEI).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] These are generally larger than small trajectory correction maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Insertion, injection and sometimes initiation are used to describe entry into a *descent orbit*, e.g. the Powered Descent Initiation maneuver used for Apollo lunar landings.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In orbital mechanics, the **Hohmann transfer orbit** is an elliptical orbit used to transfer between two circular orbits of different altitudes, in the same plane.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The orbital maneuver to perform the Hohmann transfer uses two engine impulses which move a spacecraft onto and off the transfer orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] This maneuver was named after Walter Hohmann, the German scientist who published a description of it in his 1925 book *Die Erreichbarkeit der Himmelskörper* (*The Accessibility of Celestial Bodies*).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Hohmann was influenced in part by the German science fiction author Kurd Laßwitz and his 1897 book *Two Planets*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In astronautics and aerospace engineering, the **bi-elliptic transfer** is an orbital maneuver that moves a spacecraft from one orbit to another and may, in certain situations, require less delta-v than a Hohmann transfer maneuver.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The bi-elliptic transfer consists of two half elliptic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] From the initial orbit, a delta-v is applied boosting the spacecraft into the first transfer orbit with an apoapsis at some point $r_{b}$ away from the central body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] At this point, a second delta-v is applied sending the spacecraft into the second elliptical orbit with periapsis at the radius of the final desired orbit, where a third delta-v is performed, injecting the spacecraft into the desired orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] A **low energy transfer**, or low energy trajectory, is a route in space which allows spacecraft to change orbits using very little fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] These routes work in the Earth-Moon system and also in other systems, such as traveling between the satellites of Jupiter.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The drawback of such trajectories is that they take much longer to complete than higher energy (more fuel) transfers such as Hohmann transfer orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Low energy transfer are also known as weak stability boundary trajectories, or ballistic capture trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Low energy transfers follow special pathways in space, sometimes referred to as the Interplanetary Transport Network.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Following these pathways allows for long distances to be traversed for little expenditure of delta-v.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In general, inclination changes can require a great deal of delta-v to perform, and most mission planners try to avoid them whenever possible to conserve fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] This is typically achieved by launching a spacecraft directly into the desired inclination, or as close to it as possible so as to minimize any inclination change required over the duration of the spacecraft life.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Maximum efficiency of inclination change is achieved at apoapsis, (or apogee), where orbital velocity $v\,$ is the lowest.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In some cases, it may require less total delta v to raise the spacecraft into a higher orbit, change the orbit plane at the higher apogee, and then lower the spacecraft to its original altitude.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Constant-thrust and constant-acceleration trajectories involve the spacecraft firing its engine in a prolonged constant burn.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In the limiting case where the vehicle acceleration is high compared to the local gravitational acceleration, the spacecraft points straight toward the target (accounting for target motion), and remains accelerating constantly under high thrust until it reaches its target.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In this high-thrust case, the trajectory approaches a straight line.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] If it is required that the spacecraft rendezvous with the target, rather than performing a flyby, then the spacecraft must flip its orientation halfway through the journey, and decelerate the rest of the way.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In the constant-thrust trajectory, the vehicle's acceleration increases during thrusting period, since the fuel use means the vehicle mass decreases.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] If, instead of constant thrust, the vehicle has constant acceleration, the engine thrust must decrease during the trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] This trajectory requires that the spacecraft maintain a high acceleration for long durations.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] For interplanetary transfers, days, weeks or months of constant thrusting may be required.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] As a result, there are no currently available spacecraft propulsion systems capable of using this trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] It has been suggested that some forms of nuclear (fission or fusion based) or antimatter powered rockets would be capable of this trajectory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] More practically, this type of maneuver is used in low thrust maneuvers, for example with ion engines, Hall-effect thrusters, and others.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] These types of engines have very high specific impulse (fuel efficiency) but currently are only available with fairly low absolute thrust, meaning that the thrust must be applied over a prolonged period to achieve the necessary delta-v.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] The variation of this thrust throughout the trajectory needs to be described by a comparatively large number of variables, meaning that computing such low thrust maneuvers is usually substantially more time-consuming, and less conceptually straightforward, than most high thrust impulsive maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] In astrodynamics **orbit phasing** is the adjustment of the time-position of spacecraft along its orbit, usually described as adjusting the orbiting spacecraft's true anomaly.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] A **space rendezvous** is a sequence of orbital maneuvers during which two spacecraft, one of which is often a space station, arrive at the same orbit and approach to a very close distance (e.g. within visual contact).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Rendezvous requires a precise match of the orbital velocities of the two spacecraft, allowing them to remain at a constant distance through orbital station-keeping.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-maneuver] Rendezvous is commonly followed by docking or berthing, procedures which bring the spacecraft into physical contact and create a link between them.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Celestial mechanics treats more broadly the orbit dynamics of systems under the influence of gravity, including both spacecraft and natural astronomical bodies such as star systems, planets, moons, and comets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Orbital mechanics focuses on spacecraft trajectories, including orbital maneuvers, orbital plane changes, and interplanetary transfers, and is used by mission planners to predict the results of propulsive maneuvers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] General relativity is a more exact theory than Newton's laws for calculating orbits, and it is sometimes necessary to use it for greater accuracy or in high-gravity situations (e.g. orbits near the Sun).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Until the rise of space travel in the twentieth century, there was little distinction between orbital and celestial mechanics.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] At the time of Sputnik, the field was termed **space dynamics**.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The fundamental techniques, such as those used to solve the Keplerian problem (determining position as a function of time), are therefore the same in both fields.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Furthermore, the history of the fields is almost entirely shared.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Johannes Kepler was the first to successfully model planetary orbits to a high degree of accuracy, publishing his laws in 1609.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Isaac Newton published more general laws of celestial motion in the first edition of *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (1687), which gave a method for finding the orbit of a body following a parabolic path from three observations.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This was used by Edmund Halley to establish the orbits of various comets, including that which bears his name.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Newton's method of successive approximation was formalised into an analytic method by Leonhard Euler in 1744, whose work was in turn generalised to elliptical and hyperbolic orbits by Johann Lambert in 1761–1777.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Another milestone in orbit determination was Carl Friedrich Gauss's assistance in the "recovery" of the dwarf planet Ceres in 1801.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Gauss's method was able to use just three observations (in the form of pairs of right ascension and declination), to find the six orbital elements that completely describe an orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The theory of orbit determination has subsequently been developed to the point where today it is applied in GPS receivers as well as the tracking and cataloguing of newly observed minor planets.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Modern orbit determination and prediction are used to operate all types of satellites and space probes, as it is necessary to know their future positions to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Astrodynamics was developed by astronomer Samuel Herrick beginning in the 1930s.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] He consulted the rocket scientist Robert Goddard and was encouraged to continue his work on space navigation techniques, as Goddard believed they would be needed in the future.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Numerical techniques of astrodynamics were coupled with new powerful computers in the 1960s, and humans were ready to travel to the Moon and return.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The following rules of thumb are useful for situations approximated by classical mechanics under the standard assumptions of astrodynamics outlined below.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The specific example discussed is of a satellite orbiting a planet, but the rules of thumb could also apply to other situations, such as orbits of small bodies around a star such as the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The consequences of the rules of orbital mechanics are sometimes counter-intuitive.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For example, if two spacecraft are in the same circular orbit and wish to dock, the trailing craft cannot simply fire its engines to accelerate towards the leading craft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This will change the shape of its orbit, causing it to gain altitude and slow down relative to the leading craft, thus moving away from the target.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The space rendezvous before docking normally takes multiple precisely calculated engine firings in multiple orbital periods, requiring hours or even days to complete.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] To the extent that the standard assumptions of astrodynamics do not hold, actual trajectories will vary from those calculated.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For example, simple atmospheric drag is another complicating factor for objects in low Earth orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] These rules of thumb are decidedly inaccurate when describing two or more bodies of similar mass, such as a binary star system (see n-body problem).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Celestial mechanics uses more general rules applicable to a wider variety of situations.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's laws of planetary motion, which can be mathematically derived from Newton's laws, hold strictly only in describing the motion of two gravitating bodies in the absence of non-gravitational forces; they also describe parabolic and hyperbolic trajectories.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In the close proximity of large objects like stars the differences between classical mechanics and general relativity also become important.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The fundamental laws of astrodynamics are Newton's law of universal gravitation and Newton's laws of motion, while the fundamental mathematical tool is differential calculus.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In a Newtonian framework, the laws governing orbits and trajectories are in principle time-symmetric.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Standard assumptions in astrodynamics include non-interference from outside bodies, negligible mass for one of the bodies, and negligible other forces (such as from the solar wind, atmospheric drag, etc.).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] More accurate calculations can be made without these simplifying assumptions, but they are more complicated.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The increased accuracy often does not make enough of a difference in the calculation to be worthwhile.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's laws of planetary motion may be derived from Newton's laws, when it is assumed that the orbiting body is subject only to the gravitational force of the central attractor.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] When an engine thrust or propulsive force is present, Newton's laws still apply, but Kepler's laws are invalidated.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] When the thrust stops, the resulting orbit will be different but will once again be described by Kepler's laws which have been set out above.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] A line joining a planet and the Sun sweeps out equal areas during equal intervals of time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The squares of the orbital periods of planets are directly proportional to the cubes of the semi-major axis of the orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The formula for an escape velocity is derived as follows.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The specific energy (energy per unit mass) of any space vehicle is composed of two components, the specific potential energy and the specific kinetic energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The specific potential energy associated with a planet of mass *M* is given by $\epsilon _{p}=-{\frac {GM}{r}},$ where *G* is the gravitational constant and *r* is the distance between the two bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The specific kinetic energy of an object is given by $\epsilon _{k}={\frac {v^{2}}{2}},$ where *v* is its velocity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Since energy is conserved, $\epsilon$ cannot depend on the distance, r , from the center of the central body to the space vehicle in question, i.e.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] *v* must vary with *r* to keep the specific orbital energy constant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The escape velocity from the Earth's surface is about 11 km/s, but that is insufficient to send the body an infinite distance because of the gravitational pull of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The parameter $\theta$ is known as the true anomaly, p is the semi-latus rectum, while e is the orbital eccentricity, all obtainable from the various forms of the six independent orbital elements.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] All bounded orbits where the gravity of a central body dominates are elliptical in nature.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] A special case of this is the circular orbit, which is an ellipse of zero eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Centrifugal acceleration matches the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] To properly use this formula, the units must be consistent; for example, M must be in kilograms, and r must be in meters, then the answer will be in meters per second.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The quantity $GM$ is often termed the standard gravitational parameter, which has a different value for every planet or moon in the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] To escape from gravity, the kinetic energy must at least match the negative potential energy.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] If $0<e<1$ , then the denominator of the equation of free orbits varies with the true anomaly $\theta$ , but remains positive, never becoming zero.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The maximum value r is reached when $\theta =180^{\circ }$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Let $2a$ be the distance measured along the apse line from periapsis P to apoapsis A : $2a=r_{p}+r_{a}.$ Substituting the equations above, we get $a={\frac {p}{1-e^{2}}},$ where a is the semimajor axis of the ellipse.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Under standard assumptions the orbital period ( T ) of a body traveling along an elliptic orbit can be computed as $T=2\pi {\sqrt {\frac {a^{3}}{\mu }}},$ where $\mu$ is the standard gravitational parameter, and a is the length of the semi-major axis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] As the true anomaly θ approaches 180°, the denominator approaches zero, so that *r* tends towards infinity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Hence, the energy of the trajectory for which *e* = 1 is zero, and is given by $\epsilon ={\frac {v^{2}}{2}}-{\frac {\mu }{r}}=0,$ where v is the speed of the orbiting body.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] If $e>1$ , the orbit formula $r={\frac {h^{2}}{\mu }}{\frac {1}{1+e\cos \theta }}$ describes the geometry of the hyperbolic orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The system consists of two symmetric curves.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The orbiting body occupies one of them; the other one is its empty mathematical image.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Clearly, the denominator of the equation above goes to zero when $\cos \theta =-1/e$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] We denote this value of true anomaly $\theta _{\infty }=\cos ^{-1}\left(-{\frac {1}{e}}\right),$ since the radial distance approaches infinity as the true anomaly approaches $\theta _{\infty }$ , known as the *true anomaly of the asymptote*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Observe that $\theta _{\infty }$ lies between 90° and 180°.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] One approach to calculating orbits (mainly used historically) is to use Kepler's equation: $M=E-\epsilon \sin E,$ where *M* is the mean anomaly, *E* is the eccentric anomaly, and $\epsilon$ is the eccentricity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Compute the time of flight t from the eccentric anomaly E .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Finding the eccentric anomaly at a given time (the inverse problem) is more difficult.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's equation is transcendental in E , meaning that it cannot be solved for E algebraically.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Kepler's equation can be solved for E analytically by inversion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Alternatively, Kepler's equation can be solved numerically.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] First, one must guess a value of E and solve for time of flight; then adjust E as necessary to bring the computed time of flight closer to the desired value until the required precision is achieved.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Usually, Newton's method is used to achieve relatively fast convergence.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The main difficulty with this approach is that it can take prohibitively long to converge for the extreme elliptical orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For near-parabolic orbits, eccentricity $\epsilon$ is nearly 1, and substituting $e=1$ into the formula for mean anomaly, $E-\sin E$ , we find ourselves subtracting two nearly equal values, and accuracy suffers.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For near-circular orbits, it is hard to find the periapsis in the first place (and truly circular orbits have no periapsis at all).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Furthermore, the equation was derived on the assumption of an elliptical orbit, and so it does not hold for parabolic or hyperbolic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] These difficulties are what led to the development of the universal variable formulation, described below.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For simple procedures, such as computing the delta-v for coplanar transfer ellipses, traditional approaches are fairly effective.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Others, such as time-of-flight are far more complicated, especially for near-circular and hyperbolic orbits.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The Hohmann transfer orbit alone is a poor approximation for interplanetary trajectories because it neglects the planets' own gravity.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Planetary gravity dominates the behavior of the spacecraft in the vicinity of a planet and in most cases Hohmann severely overestimates delta-v, and produces highly inaccurate prescriptions for burn timings.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] A relatively simple way to get a first-order approximation of delta-v is based on the "patched conic approximation" technique.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] One must choose the one dominant gravitating body in each region of space through which the trajectory will pass, and to model only that body's effects in that region.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For instance, on a trajectory from the Earth to Mars, one would begin by considering only the Earth's gravity until the trajectory reaches a distance where the Earth's gravity no longer dominates that of the Sun.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The spacecraft would be given escape velocity to send it on its way to interplanetary space.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Next, one would consider only the Sun's gravity until the trajectory reaches the neighborhood of Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] During this stage, the transfer orbit model is appropriate.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Finally, only Mars's gravity is considered during the final portion of the trajectory where Mars's gravity dominates the spacecraft's behavior.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The spacecraft would approach Mars on a hyperbolic orbit, and a final retrograde burn would slow the spacecraft enough to be captured by Mars.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Friedrich Zander was one of the first to apply the patched-conics approach for astrodynamics purposes, when proposing the use of intermediary bodies' gravity for interplanetary travels, in what is known today as a gravity assist.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This simplification is sufficient to compute rough estimates of fuel requirements, and rough time-of-flight estimates, but it is not generally accurate enough to guide a spacecraft to its destination.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For that, numerical methods are required.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] To address the computational shortcomings of traditional approaches for solving the 2-body problem, the universal variable formulation was developed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] It works equally well for the circular, elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic cases, the differential equations converging well when integrated for any orbit.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] It also generalizes well to problems incorporating perturbation theory.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The universal variable formulation works well with the variation of parameters technique, except now, instead of the six Keplerian orbital elements, we use a different set of orbital elements: namely, the satellite's initial position and velocity vectors $x_{0}$ and $v_{0}$ at a given epoch $t=0$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In a two-body simulation, these elements are sufficient to compute the satellite's position and velocity at any time in the future, using the universal variable formulation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Conversely, at any moment in the satellite's orbit, we can measure its position and velocity, and then use the universal variable approach to determine what its initial position and velocity *would have been* at the epoch.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In perfect two-body motion, these orbital elements would be invariant (just like the Keplerian elements would be).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] However, perturbations cause the orbital elements to change over time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Hence, the position element is written as $x_{0}(t)$ and the velocity element as $v_{0}(t)$ , indicating that they vary with time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The technique to compute the effect of perturbations becomes one of finding expressions, either exact or approximate, for the functions $x_{0}(t)$ and $v_{0}(t)$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The following are some effects which make real orbits differ from the simple models based on a spherical Earth.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Most of them can be handled on short timescales (perhaps less than a few thousand orbits) by perturbation theory because they are small relative to the corresponding two-body effects.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Over very long timescales (perhaps millions of orbits), even small perturbations can dominate, and the behavior can become chaotic.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] On the other hand, the various perturbations can be orchestrated by clever astrodynamicists to assist with orbit maintenance tasks, such as station-keeping, ground track maintenance or adjustment, or phasing of perigee to cover selected targets at low altitude.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In spaceflight, an **orbital maneuver** is the use of propulsion systems to change the orbit of a spacecraft.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For spacecraft far from Earth—for example those in orbits around the Sun—an orbital maneuver is called a *deep-space maneuver (DSM)*.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Transfer orbits are usually elliptical orbits that allow spacecraft to move from one (usually substantially circular) orbit to another.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Usually, they require a burn at the start, a burn at the end, and sometimes one or more burns in the middle.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] For the case of orbital transfer between non-coplanar orbits, the change-of-plane thrust must be made at the point where the orbital planes intersect (the "node").
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] As the objective is to change the direction of the velocity vector by an angle equal to the angle between the planes, almost all of this thrust should be made when the spacecraft is at the node near the apoapse, when the magnitude of the velocity vector is at its lowest.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] However, a small fraction of the orbital inclination change can be made at the node near the periapse, by slightly angling the transfer orbit injection thrust in the direction of the desired inclination change.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] In a gravity assist, a spacecraft swings by a planet and leaves in a different direction, at a different speed.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This is useful to speed or slow a spacecraft instead of carrying more fuel.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This maneuver can be approximated by an elastic collision at large distances, though the flyby does not involve any physical contact.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Due to Newton's third law (equal and opposite reaction), any momentum gained by a spacecraft must be lost by the planet, or vice versa.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] However, because the planet is much, much more massive than the spacecraft, the effect on the planet's orbit is negligible.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] The Oberth effect can be employed, particularly during a gravity assist operation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This effect is that use of a propulsion system works better at high speeds, and hence course changes are best done when close to a gravitating body; this can multiply the effective delta-v.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Orbital routes can be identified using nonlinear gravitational interactions between planets and moons in the Solar System.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] These trajectories are part of the Interplanetary Transport Network and follow chaotic orbital paths that require minimal fuel beyond reaching a Lagrange point, with periodic course corrections.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Orbits can be plotted from high Earth orbit to Mars via an Earth trojan points.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] Limitations include long transit times, often taking several years, and infrequent launch windows.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] They have, however, been employed on projects such as Genesis.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/orbital-mechanics] This spacecraft visited the Earth-Sun L1 point and returned using very little propellant.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Two bodies with a "slight" difference in mass orbiting a common barycenter.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] system (in which the barycenter is internal to the larger body).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] In classical mechanics, the **two-body problem** is used to calculate and predict the motion of two massive bodies that are orbiting each other in space.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The problem assumes that the two bodies are perfect spheres that never collide with one another and that all external forces are negligible compared to the force of interaction between the two bodies.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The most prominent example of the classical two-body problem is the gravitational case (see also Kepler problem), arising in astronomy for predicting the orbits (or escapes from orbit) of objects such as satellites, planets, and stars.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] A two-point-particle model of such a system nearly always describes its behavior well enough to provide useful insights and predictions.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] A simpler "one-body" model, the "central-force problem", treats one object as the immobile source of a force acting on the other.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] One then seeks to predict the motion of the single remaining mobile object.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Such an approximation can give useful results when one object is much more massive than the other (as with a light planet orbiting a heavy star, where the star can be treated as essentially stationary).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] However, the one-body approximation is usually unnecessary except as a stepping stone.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] For many forces, including gravitational ones, the general version of the two-body problem can be reduced to a pair of one-body problems, allowing it to be solved completely, and giving a solution simple enough to be used effectively.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] By contrast, the three-body problem (and, more generally, the *n*-body problem for *n* > 2) cannot be solved generally, except in special cases.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Under the force of gravity, each member of a pair of such objects will orbit their mutual center of mass in an elliptical pattern, unless they are moving fast enough to escape one another entirely, in which case their paths will diverge along other planar conic sections.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] If one object is very much heavier than the other, it will move far less than the other with reference to the shared center of mass.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The mutual center of mass may even be inside the larger object.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] For the derivation of the solutions to the problem, see Classical central-force problem or Kepler problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] In principle, the same solutions apply to macroscopic problems involving objects interacting not only through gravity, but also through any conservative force obeying the inverse-square law, with electrostatic attraction being an obvious physical example.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] In practice, such problems rarely arise.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Except perhaps in experimental apparatus or other specialized equipment, we rarely encounter electrostatically interacting objects which are moving fast enough, and in such a direction, as to avoid colliding, and/or which are isolated enough from their surroundings.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The dynamical system of a two-body system under the influence of torque turns out to be a Sturm-Liouville equation.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Although we can describe the repulsion and attraction of particles in the atom using the same laws that apply to the leaves of an electroscope, we need quantum mechanics to predict how the particles will behave under those forces.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Most behavior of subatomic systems *cannot* be predicted under the classical assumptions underlying this article or using the mathematics here.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Electrons in an atom are sometimes described as "orbiting" its nucleus, following an early conjecture of Niels Bohr (this is the source of the term "orbital").
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] However, electrons don't actually orbit nuclei in any meaningful sense, and quantum mechanics are necessary for any useful understanding of the electron's real behavior.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Solving the classical two-body problem for an electron orbiting an atomic nucleus is misleading and does not produce many useful insights.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The complete two-body problem can be solved by re-formulating it as two one-body problems: a trivial one and one that involves solving for the motion of one particle in an external potential.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Since many one-body problems can be solved exactly, the corresponding two-body problem can also be solved.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Let **x**1 and **x**2 be the vector positions of the two bodies, and *m*1 and *m*2 be their masses.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] where **F**12 is the force on mass 1 due to its interactions with mass 2, and **F**21 is the force on mass 2 due to its interactions with mass 1.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The two dots on top of the **x** position vectors denote their second derivative with respect to time, or their acceleration vectors.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Adding and subtracting these two equations decouples them into two one-body problems, which can be solved independently.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] *Adding* equations (1) and (**2**) results in an equation describing the center of mass (barycenter) motion.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] By contrast, *subtracting* equation (2) from equation (1) results in an equation that describes how the vector **r** = **x**1 − **x**2 between the masses changes with time.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The solutions of these independent one-body problems can be combined to obtain the solutions for the trajectories **x**1(*t*) and **x**2(*t*).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Let $\mathbf {R}$ be the position of the center of mass (barycenter) of the system.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The resulting equation: ${\ddot {\mathbf {R} }}=0$ shows that the velocity $\mathbf {v} ={\frac {dR}{dt}}$ of the center of mass is constant, from which follows that the total momentum *m*1 **v**1 + *m*2 **v**2 is also constant (conservation of momentum).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Hence, the position **R**(*t*) of the center of mass can be determined at all times from the initial positions and velocities.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The force between the two objects, which originates in the two objects, should only be a function of their separation **r** and not of their absolute positions **x**1 and **x**2; otherwise, there would not be translational symmetry, and the laws of physics would have to change from place to place.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Solving the equation for **r**(*t*) is the key to the two-body problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The solution depends on the specific force between the bodies, which is defined by $\mathbf {F} (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] For the case where $\mathbf {F} (\mathbf {r} )$ follows an inverse-square law, see the Kepler problem.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] The motion of two bodies with respect to each other always lies in a plane (in the center of mass frame).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Introducing the assumption (true of most physical forces, as they obey Newton's strong third law of motion) that the force between two particles acts along the line between their positions, it follows that **r** × **F** = **0** and the angular momentum vector **L** is constant (conserved).
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] Therefore, the displacement vector **r** and its velocity **v** are always in the plane perpendicular to the constant vector **L**.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] For many physical problems, the force **F**(**r**) is a central force, i.e., it is of the form $\mathbf {F} (\mathbf {r} )=F(r){\hat {\mathbf {r} }}$ where *r* = |**r**| and **r̂** = **r**/*r* is the corresponding unit vector.
[src:orbital-mechanics-applied/two-body-problem] We now have: $\mu {\ddot {\mathbf {r} }}={F}(r){\hat {\mathbf {r} }}\ ,$ where *F*(*r*) is negative in the case of an attractive force.
